Ringgit Climbs on Expected Rate Rise, Inflation; Bonds Decline

-- B y   D a v i d   Y o n g
-- 
2011-07-07T08:27:25Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-07/ringgit-climbs-on-expected-rate-rise-inflation-bonds-decline.html
Malaysia’s ringgit gained on
speculation higher  interest rates  will bolster overseas demand
for local assets as policy makers seek to damp the fastest
inflation in more than two years.  The currency snapped a two-day decline as 10 of 15
economists forecast that  Bank Negara Malaysia  will raise its
overnight rate to 3.25 percent from 3 percent today, overriding
concern that the economy is slowing. Five predicted no change.
Consumer prices rose 3.3 percent in May from a year earlier, the
most since March 2009. Five-year bonds dropped before a
government debt sale next week.  “A rate hike will be needed to anchor inflation
expectations and this is supportive of the ringgit,” said
Choong Yin Pheng, manager for economic and fixed-income research
at Hong Leong Bank Bhd. in  Kuala Lumpur . “The growth outlook is
a concern but we are not seeing a full-blown slowdown.”  The ringgit gained 0.1 percent to 3.0100 per dollar as of
4:18 p.m. in Kuala Lumpur, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. The currency has risen 0.3 percent his month,
following losses in May and June.  Bank Negara  last raised its policy rate on May 5 by a
quarter of a percentage point, saying growth remains on a steady
path and inflation will quicken in the second half. The
benchmark rate compares with a range of zero to 0.25 percent in
the U.S.  Today’s decision is expected after 6 p.m. in Kuala Lumpur.  Bond Auction  Global funds raised their holdings in ringgit-denominated
debt by 5 percent to a record 181.5 billion ringgit ($60.3
billion) in May, according to central bank statistics.  The yield on the 4.262 percent bond due September 2016 rose
seven basis points, or 0.07 percentage point, to 3.58 percent,
according to Bursa Malaysia. The price declined 0.35, or 3.5
ringgit per 1,000 ringgit face amount, to 103.2.  The treasury will auction an additional 4 billion ringgit
of the 2016 notes on July 13, the central bank announced on its
website today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
David Yong in  Singapore  at 
 dyong@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
